[p 
	"Just to ensure the whole run is like that, I also tried to improve your room that goes at frame 19717. By reapplying Masterjun's strats, I saved 4 frames there too. Not providing the example movie, because all this is very trivial and obvious.
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"Note that it's barely possible to compare actual frame-wise timings to Masterun's record, because the Windows version of VVVVVV duplicates every other frame and also runs at 60 fps, while the version used here uses 29.412 fps and doesn't duplicate frames. So all that's there to compare is strats and techniques. And in that regard, you're losing to an existing record, which breaks 
	[a class=intlink href=/MovieRules#SpeedOrientedMovieMustBeatAllExistingRecords 
		"another one of our Movie Rules
	]a
	". This could have been avoided, if you followed out 
	(__wikiLink|/Guidelines|Guidelines)
	" and 
	[a class=intlink href=/Guidelines#DoPossibleResearch 
		"did due research
	]a
	" in advance, before considering your movie complete.
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"The third problem with this submission is its goals. What we expect from the goals of a given movie is mentioned 
	[a class=intlink href=/MovieRules#Moons_2 
		"in the Rules
	]a
	", how goals relate to our 
	(__wikiLink|/Tier|Tier)
	" system is explained 
	[a class=intlink href=/Guidelines#Tiers 
		"in the Guidelines
	]a
	", and more insight on how to select your goals is described in details 
	[a class=intlink href=/Guidelines#SelectYourGoalsWell 
		"in this particular paragraph
	]a
	".
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"This movie can't be considered 
	(__wikiLink|/FastestCompletion|Fastest Completion)
	" category by our standards, so it can't go to 
	(__wikiLink|/Vault|Vault)
	". It has to be entertaining to the general audience and to represent some unique content with what it selects to accomplish in addition to going fast. So what does it accomplish?
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"It avoids 
	[a class=intlink href=/4302S#TeleflingingTelejumping 
		"telejumping
	]a
	", which was introduced by 
	[a class=intlink href=/2597M 
		"this movie
	]a
	". Even though the run that movie obsoletes had a star, 
	[a class=intlink href=/Forum/T/15318 
		"it was decided
	]a
	" to still obsolete the run with no telejumping by the run that has it. Which means, telejumping alone is not the kind of trick that could spawn new branches distinguished solely by its usage.
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"Moreover, we already have a movie that forbids telejumping! 
	(__wikiLink|/2715M|2715M)
	" avoids such glitches to bring back the enjoyment the previously mentioned starred (and obsoleted) run was providing. So this particular restriction is nothing unique compared to existing branches of this game.
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"The "least checkpoints" goal is even less meaningful. While "no telejumping" can be a part of some other goal, like glitchless full completion, minimizing the amount of checkpoints one activates adds nothing novel at all. The audience showed no interest in this condition, instead it was several times mentioned how pointless this goal is. And indeed, there's really nothing outstanding it could add to a TAS (aside from confusion). It is an example of a blatantly arbitrary goal, like "jumping at least thrice in every room" of Super Mario Bros. Unlike 
	[a class=intlink href=/MovieClassGuidelines#PacifistVersion 
		"avoiding kills
	]a
	" which can be really challenging in some games, and also has some humanist appeal to it, in a VVVVVV TAS, avoiding checkpoints adds no challenge and no appeal.
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"Finally, this is a case when a game has nearly identical versions across platforms, so Linux and Windows versions of VVVVVV can obsolete one another if needed, and if there's general consensus about actual cases. As usual, if some version is so different that it features obviously unique tricks and glitches, it can be published just because the run showcases them. Or some branch can use a specific version to increase the diversity. But 
	[em 
		"similar
	]em
	" branches of different PC versions of VVVVVV will not be accepted.
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"All in all, thanks for trying, and don't lose your energy over this rejection, but next time, 
	[em 
		"please consider
	]em
	" all the rules and guidelines I linked here. Following the discussion thread for your submission is also important. Rejecting for numerous reasons.
